{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/obstructive-sleep-apnoea-syndrome/background-information/complications-prognosis/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"ee60def2-e745-5cf3-91c2-a6fb72b5659f","slug":"complications-prognosis","fullItemName":"Complications and prognosis","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 8acee665-239c-48e9-b346-5ed4eca3c7d7 --><h2>What are the complications and prognosis?</h2><!-- end field 8acee665-239c-48e9-b346-5ed4eca3c7d7 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 219f851c-6f6f-45db-b9fe-161b56e8dc3b --><!-- begin field 20c520c9-1286-45fa-b98e-ae89588bbb50 --><ul><li><strong>The complications of obstructive sleep apnoea syndrome (OSAS):</strong><ul><li><strong>In adults include:</strong><ul><li>Hypertension — some authors propose that OSAS has an independent role in the pathogenesis of hypertension [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/obstructive-sleep-apnoea-syndrome/references/\">Parati et al, 2013</a>].</li><li>Stroke — 5 studies (n = 8435) from a systematic review and a meta-analysis concluded that OSAS increases the risk of stroke independently of other cerebrovascular risk factors [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/obstructive-sleep-apnoea-syndrome/references/\">Loke et al, 2012</a>].</li><li>Road traffic accidents — untreated OSAS is associated with a 7–12 times increased risk of road traffic accidents compared with people without OSAS [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/obstructive-sleep-apnoea-syndrome/references/\">Pagel, 2007</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>In children include </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/obstructive-sleep-apnoea-syndrome/references/\">Powell et al, 2010</a>]<strong>:</strong><ul><li>Behavioural problems, irritability, poor concentration, and poor school performance.</li><li>Faltering growth (in severe cases).</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>The prognosis of treated OSAS:</strong><ul><li><strong>In adults</strong><ul><li>Continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP) treatment reduces daytime and nocturnal blood pressure [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/obstructive-sleep-apnoea-syndrome/references/\">Greenstone and Hack, 2014</a>]. A meta-analysis of 28 studies found a weighted mean difference in diurnal systolic blood pressure of –2.58 mmHg and diastolic blood pressure of –2.01 mmHg. Similar results were found with nocturnal readings [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/obstructive-sleep-apnoea-syndrome/references/\">Montesi et al, 2012</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>In children</strong><ul><li>A meta–analysis has shown a reduction in sleep apnoea severity, and an improvement in quality of life in children after adenotonsillectomy [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/obstructive-sleep-apnoea-syndrome/references/\">Powell et al, 2010</a>].</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 20c520c9-1286-45fa-b98e-ae89588bbb50 --><!-- end item 219f851c-6f6f-45db-b9fe-161b56e8dc3b -->","topic":{"id":"f1196501-9004-50dc-b7d4-52b757fd68f1","topicId":"f39c3a30-1d8b-4e7f-b393-c9630f5cc63e","topicName":"Obstructive sleep apnoea syndrome","slug":"obstructive-sleep-apnoea-syndrome","lastRevised":"Last revised in April 2015","chapters":[{"id":"bc5b27b2-fcc2-5d5f-9226-645ee30f74c0","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"6f088cf7-eb48-5367-8924-56f6b7bc8a09","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"038fcffa-9056-5240-9299-e41f1639e4a7","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"1a571c23-537f-5a82-a38a-7c305b7fa5f4","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"cb715fc0-8cc6-5416-9b8a-2ec36869